                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d4">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4 General Committee (Arms)/81:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        American Adviser</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Mayer</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-01-16T14:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 16, 1935—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>467. My 466, January 15, 8 p.m. On further consideration, we think it advisable
                    for you to seek a clarification of the situation through a frank talk with
                        Eden.<note n="13" xml:id="d4fn13">Anthony Eden, Lord Privy Seal and British
                        representative on the Council of the League of Nations.</note> After
                    speaking to him along the lines authorized in our 466, you might add a reference
                    to the unfortunate repercussions in the United States of any delay in dealing
                    with a <pb facs="0106" n="4" xml:id="pg_4"/> problem in which the American
                    public and the American Congress are particularly interested at this time.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
